<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-multiplying-matrices-i" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Multiplying Matrices I</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.7 Matrices I
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Multiply compatible matrices in different situations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on activity -->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To provide an rationale for the formula for matrix-vector multiplication formula and introduce it through a practical example.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="mango-shopping-2">
        <statement>
            <p> We continue with Kelvin and Esther from <xref ref="mango-shopping"/>. As a reminder, this matrix represents their purchases of mangoes, oranges, and bananas from the shop in Soy:
            <md>
                S = \begin{bmatrix}  5 &amp; 2 &amp; 1 \\ 6 &amp; 1 &amp; 3 \end{bmatrix}
            </md>
            The first column tells us that Kelvin bought 5 mangoes and Esther bought 6 mangoes.
            </p>    
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            If mangoes cost Ksh 10 each, oranges cost Ksh 15 each, and bananas cost Ksh 5 each, how much does Kelvin spend at the shop in total?
                        </p>
                        <solution component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>
                                Kelvin spends <m>5 \times 10 + 2 \times 15 + 1 \times 5 = \text{Ksh } 85</m>.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                        <note component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>  Help Learners break this up by fruit if they are struggling
                            </p>
                        </note>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            What about Esther?
                        </p>
                        <solution component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>
                                Esther spends <m>6 \times 10 + 1 \times 15 + 3 \times 5 = \text{Ksh } 90</m>.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Could you write the costs as a matrix? What shape might it take?
                        </p>
                        <note component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>
                            Learners might write the costs as a <m>1\times3</m> matrix, like so: <me>\mathbf{x} = \begin{bmatrix} 10 &amp; 15 &amp; 5 \end{bmatrix}</me>.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Or they might write the costs as a <m>3\times1</m> matrix, like so: <me>\mathbf{x} = \begin{bmatrix} 10 \\ 15 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix}</me>.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Encourage both representations, and show Learners a different option if they only provide one. Foreshadow that the second representation will be more useful for matrix-vector multiplication.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Learners should not have units (like Ksh) in their matrix, but understand that these entries represent quantities of money.
                            </p>
                        </note>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            If mangoes cost Ksh <m>x</m>, oranges cost Ksh <m>y</m>, and bananas cost Ksh <m>z</m>, can you create an expression for how much Kelvin spends?
                        </p>
                        <solution component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>
                                Kelvin spends <m>5 \times x + 2 \times y + 1 \times z</m>. 
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </li>              
                    </ol>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on structured lesson plan-->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalize the concepts and properties learners discovered in the anchor task.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Matrix-vector multiplication is tricky for Learners; take your time with this formula. 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>
    

    <insight>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <term>Matrix-vector multiplication</term> combines a matrix with a vector to produce a new vector.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    A matrix can only multiply a vector if the number of columns in the matrix equals the number of entries in the vector. The <term>inner dimensions</term> must match.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Matrix-vector multiplication produces a vector with the same number of columns as the matrix.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            Suppose that <m>A</m> is a <m>2 \times 3</m> matrix and <m>\mathbf{v}</m> is a <m>3 \times 1</m> vector, with <me>A = \begin{bmatrix}\color{blue}{a} \amp \color{blue}{b} \amp \color{blue}{c}\\ \color{red}{d} \amp \color{red}{e} \amp \color{red}{f}\end{bmatrix},\quad \mathbf{v} = \begin{bmatrix}\color{teal}{x}\\ \color{teal}{y}\\ \color{teal}{z}\end{bmatrix}</me>.
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The product <m>A \mathbf{v}</m> is defined since the inner dimensions match: <m>A</m> has 3 columns and <m>v</m> has 3 rows.
                </p>
            </li> 
            <li> 
                <p> 
                    <m>A \mathbf{v}</m> is a <m>2 \times 1</m> vector given by: <me>
                        Av = \begin{bmatrix} \color{blue}{a}\color{teal}{x} \,\color{black}{+}\, \color{blue}{b}\color{teal}{y} \,\color{black}{+}\, \color{blue}{c}\color{teal}{z} \\ \color{red}{d}\color{teal}{x} \,\color{black}{+}\, \color{red}{e}\color{teal}{y} \,\color{black}{+}\, \color{red}{f}\color{teal}{z} \end{bmatrix}
                    </me>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Each entry of <m>Av</m> is a <em>row</em> of <m>A</m> multiplied by the vector <m>v</m> (matching components multiplied and then added).
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </insight>

        <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                As in <xref ref="mango-shopping-2"/>, let <m>\mathbf{S} = \begin{bmatrix}  5 &amp; 2 &amp; 1 \\ 6 &amp; 1 &amp; 3 \end{bmatrix}</m> be the quantities of mangoes, oranges, and banans bought by Kelvin (first row) and Esther (second row). Suppose the cost vector is given by:
                <md>
                    \mathbf{x} = \begin{bmatrix} 10 \\ 15 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix}
                </md>
                Calculate <m>S\mathbf{x}</m>, and compare your answers to the Learner Experience.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Calculating the matrix-vector multiplication:
                <md>
                    <mrow>S \mathbf{x} \amp =  \begin{bmatrix}  5 &amp; 2 &amp; 1 \\ 6 &amp; 1 &amp; 3 \end{bmatrix}  \begin{bmatrix} 10 \\ 15 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix}5(10) + 2(15) + 1(5) \\ 6(10) + 1(15) + 3(5)\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix}85 \\ 90\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                </md>
                This is the total cost for Kelvin and Esther (respectively) that we found in the Learner Experience.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Properties of Matrix-Vector Multiplication</title>
      <p>For the matrices <m>A,B</m> of size <m>m\times n</m> and vectors <m>\mathbf{x}, \mathbf{y}</m> of size <m>n \times 1</m> the following properties hold:
      <ul cols="2">
        <li><m>A\left(\mathbf{x} + \mathbf{y}\right) = A\mathbf{x} + A\mathbf{y}</m>
        </li>
        <li><m>A\left(\mathbf{x} - \mathbf{y}\right) = A\mathbf{x} - A\mathbf{y}</m>
        </li>
        <li><m>(A+B)\mathbf{x} = A\mathbf{x} + B\mathbf{x}</m>
        </li>
        <li><m>(A-B)\mathbf{x} = A\mathbf{x} - B\mathbf{x}</m>
        </li>
      </ul>
        </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Given <m>A = \begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp -1\end{bmatrix}</m> and vectors <m>\mathbf{x} = \begin{bmatrix}4 \\ 1\end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\mathbf{y} = \begin{bmatrix}-3 \\ 3\end{bmatrix}</m>, confirm that: <md>A\left(\mathbf{x} + \mathbf{y}\right) = A\mathbf{x} + A\mathbf{y}</md>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Firstly,
                <md>
                    <mrow> A\left(\mathbf{x} + \mathbf{y}\right) \amp = \begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp -1\end{bmatrix}\left(\begin{bmatrix}4 \\ 1\end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix}-3 \\ 3\end{bmatrix}\right) </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp -1\end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 4\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix}2(1) + 1(4) \\ 0(1) + (-1)(4)\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix}6 \\ -4\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                </md>
                Additionally,
                <md>
                    <mrow> A\mathbf{x} + A\mathbf{y}\amp = \begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp -1\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}4 \\ 1\end{bmatrix} +\begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp -1\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}-3 \\ 3\end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix}2(4) + 1(1) \\ 0(4) + (-1)(1)\end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} 2(-3) + 1(3) \\ 0(-3) + (-1)(3)\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix}9 \\ -1\end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} -3 \\ -3\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix}6 \\ -4\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                </md>
                Thus <m>A\left(\mathbf{x} + \mathbf{y}\right) = A\mathbf{x} + A\mathbf{y}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <paragraphs>
        <title>Multiplying a Matrix by a Scalar</title>
        <p>
            Multiplying a matrix by a scalar (a real number) is simple; just multiply each entry in the matrix by that scalar:
            <md>
                2\begin{bmatrix}a \amp b \amp c \\ d \amp e \amp f \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}2a \amp 2b \amp 2c \\ 2d \amp 2e \amp 2f \end{bmatrix}
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            If <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m> are a real numbers and <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are <m>m \times n</m> matrices, then the following are true:
            <ul cols="2">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\alpha\left(A + B\right) = \alpha A + \alpha B</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\alpha\left(A - B\right) = \alpha A - \alpha B</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>(\alpha + \beta)A = \alpha A + \beta A </m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>(\alpha - \beta)A = \alpha A - \beta A </m>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Given <m>A = \begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp -1\end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>B = \begin{bmatrix}-1 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}</m>, confirm that <md>-3(A+B) = -3A - 3B</md>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Working with the left hand side, we have:
                <md>
                    <mrow>-3(A+B) \amp = -3\left(\begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp -1\end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix}-1 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}\right)</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = -3 \begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 5 \\ 0 \amp -1\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix}-3 \amp -15 \\ 0 \amp 3\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                </md>
                And on the right hand side:
                <md>
                    <mrow>-3A - 3B \amp = -3\begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp -1\end{bmatrix} -3\begin{bmatrix}-1 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp 0\end{bmatrix} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix}-6 \amp -3 \\ 0 \amp 3 \end{bmatrix} - \begin{bmatrix}-3 \amp 12 \\ 0 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix}-3 \amp -15 \\ 0 \amp 3\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                </md>
                Thus <m>-3(A+B) = -3A - 3B</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

